 82,274\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| 1\n|-\n| bgcolor=lightgrey| [[2016 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|2016]]\n| bgcolor=lightgrey| 18 September\n| bgcolor=lightgrey| [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]]\n| bgcolor=lightgrey| 2-9\n| bgcolor=lightgrey| Mayo\n| bgcolor=lightgrey| 0-15\n| bgcolor=lightgrey| [[Croke Park]]\n| bgcolor=lightgrey| 82,257\n| bgcolor=lightgrey| n/a (Draw)\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| [[2016 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|2016]]\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| 1 October\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]]\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| 1-15\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| Mayo\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| 1-14\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| [[Croke Park]]\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| 82,249\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| 1 (Replay)\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| [[2017 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|2017]]\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| 17 September\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]]\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| 1-17\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| Mayo\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| 1-16\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| [[Croke Park]]\n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| \n| bgcolor=\"#FBCEB1\"| 1\n|-\n|}\n\n==Hurling==\n{{Further|Mayo Senior Hurling Championship}}\nAlthough not a traditional hurling county, hurling is strong in certain parts of the county especially in the eastern region around [[Ballyhaunis]] and Tooreen. There are 4 Senior hurling clubs in Mayo, who compete for the TJ Tyrell Senior Hurling Championship each year. These 4 clubs are [[Tooreen Hurling Club|Tooreen]], [[Ballyhaunis GAA|Ballyhaunis]], [[Castlebar Mitchels GAA|Castlebar Mitchels]], Westport. [[Ballyhaunis GAA|Ballyhaunis]] are the reigning Senior Champions and have 6 senior titles, while Tooreen hold the most titles with 26.\n\nThese 4 clubs provide the players to the Mayo Senior hurling panel, who take part in the National Hurling League and in the All-Ireland Christy Ring (Tier 2) Cup. Mayo's best performances in the Christy Ring Cup came in 2008 and 2009, when the Mayo side fell at the semi-final stage to Carlow and Down respectively. The Mayo U-21 hurling team compete in the Connacht U-21B hurling championship each year along with Roscommon, Sligo and Leitrim.\n\nHurling at underage level is also expanding in Mayo, with 10 clubs competing in underage leagues and championships in the county. As well as the 6 adult sides named above, 4 other underage clubs have formed in recent years. These clubs are Ballyvary, Moytura, Caiseal Gaels and Claremorris. These 10 clubs provide the players for the Mayo underage hurling development panels. Mayo have development panels at U14, U15, U16 and Minor age-groups, and compete in the All-Ireland 'B' competitions each year.\n\nMayo's most famous hurlers are Joe Henry (Tooreen), who won Railway Cup medals with Connacht in the 1980s, and current dual player Keith Higgins (Ballyhaunis) who played for the Mayo football team in the All-Ireland football final in 2006, 2012, 2103 and 2016.\n\nHurling in Mayo is administered by the Mayo GAA Hurling Committee, which is a sub-committee of the Mayo GAA County Board.\nIn 2016 Mayo won the Nicky Rackard cup beating Armagh 2-16 to 1-15 in Croke Park\n\n===Current hurling squad===\n*[[Manager (Gaelic games)|Manager]]: Derek Walsh\n{{GAA squad start}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=1|pos=Goalkeeper|name=Martin Parsons|club=[[Castlebar Mitchels GAA|Castlebar Mitchels]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=2|pos=Right Corner Back|name=Brian Hunt|club=[[Ballyhaunis GAA|Ballyhaunis]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=3|pos=Full Back|name=Aiden Connolly|club=[[Westport GAA|Westport]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=4|pos=Left Corner Back|name=Eoghan Collins|club=[[Ballyhaunis GAA|Ballyhaunis]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=5|pos=Right Half Back|name=Declan Gallagher|club=[[Westport GAA|Westport]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=6|pos=Centre Back|name=David Kenny|club=[[Tooreen Hurling Club|Tooreen]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=7|pos=Left Half Back|name=Ciaran Finn|club=[[Tooreen Hurling Club|Tooreen]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=8|pos=Midfield|name=Kieran McDermott|club=[[Ballyhaunis GAA|Ballyhaunis]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=9|pos=Midfield|name=Padraig O\u2019Flynn |club=[[Castlegar GAA|Castlegar]] ([[Galway GAA|Galway]])}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=10|pos=Right Half Forward|name=Austin Lyons|club=[[Ballyhaunis GAA|Ballyhaunis]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=11|pos=Centre Forward|name=Kenny Feeney|club=[[Tooreen Hurling Club|Tooreen]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=12|pos=Left Half Forward|name=Fergal Boland|club=[[Tooreen Hurling Club|Tooreen]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=13|pos=Right Corner Forward|name=Stephen Hoban|club=[[Ballyhaunis GAA|Ballyhaunis]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=14|pos=Full Forward|name=Sean Regan|club=[[James Stephens GAA (Mayo)|James Stephens]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=15|pos=Left Corner Forward|name=Darren McTigue|club=[[Castlebar Mitchels GAA|Castlebar Mitchels]]}}\n{{GAA squad mid}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=16|pos=Substitute|name=Davog Freyne|club=[[Tooreen Hurling Club|Tooreen]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=17|pos=Substitute|name=Adrian Brennan|club=[[Ballyhaunis GAA|Ballyhaunis]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=18|pos=Substitute|name=Shane Boland|club=[[Tooreen Hurling Club|Tooreen]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=19|pos=Substitute|name=Kieran Kiely|club=[[Ballyhaunis GAA|Ballyhaunis]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=20|pos=Substitute|name=Luke Cribben|club=[[Ballyhaunis GAA|Ballyhaunis]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=21|pos=Substitute|name=Fergal Lyons|club=[[Ballyhaunis GAA|Ballyhaunis]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=22|pos=Substitute|name=Gary Nolan|club=[[Tooreen Hurling Club|Tooreen]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=23|pos=Substitute|name=Shane Morley|club=[[Tooreen Hurling Club|Tooreen]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=24|pos=Substitute|name=Joe Ganley|club=[[Tooreen Hurling Club|Tooreen]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=25|pos=Substitute|name=David Garrison|club=[[Tooreen Hurling Club|Tooreen]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=26|pos=Substitute|name=Corey Scahill|club=[[Castlebar Mitchels GAA|Castlebar Mitchels]]}}\n{{GAA squad end}}\nSquad as per Mayo vs [[Derry GAA|Derry]], [[Christy Ring Cup]] Round 1, May 2, 2015\n\n===Honours===\n'''All Irelands'''\n\n* 1  '''[[Nicky Rackard Cup]]'''\n** [[2016 Nicky Rackard Cup|2016]]\n* 3 '''[[All-Ireland Junior Hurling Championship|All-Ireland Junior Hurling Championships]]'''\n** 1980, 1981, 2003\n* 2 '''All-Ireland Minor 'C' Hurling Championships'''\n** 2013, 2014\n\n\n\n'''Provincials'''\n\n* 1 '''[[Connacht Senior Hurling Championship]]'''\n** 1909\n*2 '''[[Connacht Intermediate Hurling Championship]]'''\n** 1969, 2014\n*3 '''[[Connacht Junior Hurling Championship|Connacht Junior Hurling Championships]]'''\n** 1936, 1967, 2004\n*2 '''Jim Hogan Couriers Connaught U21 Hurling Championship'''\n** 2015, 2016\n* 1 '''[[Connacht Minor Hurling Championship]]s'''\n** 1964\n\n==Ladies' Gaelic football==\n{{Expand section|date=June 2008}}\n\n===Honours===\n* 4 '''[[All-Ireland Senior Ladies' Football Championship]]s'''\n** 1999, 2000, 2002, 2003\n* Three times '''All-Ireland Senior Ladies' Football Finalists'''\n** 2001, 2007,2017\n* 1 '''[[All-Ireland Junior Ladies' Football Championship]]'''\n** 1987\n* 1 '''[[All-Ireland Intermediate Ladies' Football Championship]]'''\n** 1993\n* 1 '''[[All-Ireland Under-18 Ladies' Football Championship]]'''\n** 1987\n* 2 '''[[All-Ireland Under-16 Ladies' Football Championship]]s'''\n** 1976, 2010\n* 2 '''[[All-Ireland Under-14 Ladies' Football Championship]]s'''\n** 1994, 2010\n\n==Camogie==\nMayo contested the [[All-Ireland Senior Camogie Championship]] final of 1959, captained by Josie Ruane from Menulla. Na Br\u00eddeoga won the Coiste Chontae an Chl\u00e1ir Shield at [[F\u00e9ile na nGael]] in 2009, Parke (1983) and Ardagh (1988) had previously won divisional honours.\n\nThe county hosted the 2007 [[All-Ireland Junior Camogie Championship#M\u00e1ire N\u00ed Chinn\u00e9ide Cup|M\u00e1ire N\u00ed Chinn\u00e9ide Cup]].<ref>2007 M\u00e1ire N\u00ed Chinn\u00e9ide Cup report in [http://www.anfearrua.com/story.asp?id=2430 Anfearua.com] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224055833/http://anfearrua.com/story.asp?id=2430 |date=24 December 2010 }} and [http://archives.tcm.ie/westernpeople/2007/08/29/story37941.asp Western People] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629124044/http://archives.tcm.ie/westernpeople/2007/08/29/story37941.asp |date=29 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\nUnder Camogie's National Development Plan 2010\u20132015, \u201cOur Game, Our Passion,\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/hurling/final-goal-for-camogie-2115510.html|title=Final goal for camogie|newspaper=Irish Independent|publisher=Independent News & Media|date=29 March 2010|accessdate=29 March 2010}}</ref> [[Donegal GAA#Camogie|Donegal]], [[Kerry GAA#Camogie|Kerry]], Mayo and [[Monaghan GAA#Camogie|Monaghan]] are to get a total of 14 new clubs by 2015.<ref>National Development Plan 2010\u20132015, Our Game, Our Passion information page on [http://www.camogie.ie/NationalDevelopmentPlan/tabid/71/Default.aspx camogie.ie], pdf download (778k) from [http://www.camogie.ie/Portals/0/Documents/Development%20Plan.pdf Camogie.ie download site]</ref>\n\n==Notable players==\n* [[Gabriel Irwin]]\n* [[Alan Dillon]]\n* [[Ciar\u00e1n McDonald]]\n* [[Liam McHale]]\n* [[Colm McManamon]]\n* [[Michael Moyles]]\n* [[Willie Joe Padden]]\n* [[Stephen Rochford]]\n* [[Andy Moran]]\n* [[Conor Mortimer]]\nRory Smith\n\n==Supporter Songs==\n* Boys from the County Mayo - [[Margo (singer)|Margo]]\n* Hay Wrap - [[The Saw Doctors]]\n* In the Name of Mayo - The Duffys\n* [[The Green and Red of Mayo]] - [[The Saw Doctors]]\n* To Win Just Once - [[The Saw Doctors]]\n* Mayo are Back - [[Mike Denver]]\n* This will be our year \u2013 [[Nicole Gannon]]\n* Mayo for Sam \u2013 [[Chris and Dave]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KsoB8Z1ukMU</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Clune, M. A. (1954) ''Mayo's Football Triumphs''. Dublin: Pearse Press\n* Reilly, Terry & Neill, Ivan (1985) ''The Green Above the Red: a compilation of Mayo's All-Ireland triumphs at all levels''. Ballina: Western People\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n1. [http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2008/0804/1217628486219.html]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.mayogaa.com/ Mayo GAA site]\n* [http://www.mayoclub51.com/ Mayo Club '51]\n* [http://www.hoganstand.com/Mayo/ Mayo] on Hoganstand.com\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170702202421/http://www.hoganstand.com/Mayo/Profile.aspx National and provincial titles won by Mayo teams]\n* [http://www.mayogaablog.com/ ''Green and Red'', a Mayo GAA blog]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110721122954/http://www.clubmayo.ie/ Club Mayo Dublin]\n\n{{Mayo GAA}}\n{{Mayo Football Team}}\n{{Mayo GAA clubs}}\n{{Mayo Senior Football Championship}}\n{{GAA National Leagues|Christy Ring Cup}}\n{{GAA bodies}}\n\n[[Category:Mayo GAA| ]]\n[[Category:Gaelic games governing bodies in Connacht]]\n[[Category:Sport in County Mayo]]\n[[Category:Sports-related curses]]\n", "text_old": "{{dablink|For more details of Mayo GAA see [[Mayo Senior Club Football Championship]] or [[Mayo Senior Club Hurling Championship]].}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{infobox GAA county\n| county gaa      = Mayo GAA\n| county colours  = Green, Red\n{{Color box|#006400}} {{Color box|#FF0000}}\n| crest           = [[File:Mayo crest.JPG|180px]]\n| irish           = Maigh Eo\n| province        = Connacht\n| nickname        = ''The Westerners''<br/>''The Yew County''<br/>''The Heather County''\n| grounds         = [[MacHale Park]], [[Castlebar]]\n| dominant sport  = Gaelic football\n| nfl div         = Division 1\n| nhl div         = Division 2A\n| football champ  = Sam Maguire Cup\n| hurling champ   = Nicky Rackard\n| ladies football = Brendan Martin Cup\n| camogie         = \n|pattern_la=_mayo17|pattern_b=_mayo17|pattern_ra=_mayo17|pattern_sh=_red stripes adidas|pattern_so=_juve0506a|\nleftarm=185E0B |body=185E0B |rightarm=185E0B |shorts=FFFFFF |socks=ff0000\n|pattern_la2=_mayoa17|pattern_b2=_mayo17a|pattern_ra2=_mayoa17|pattern_sh2=|pattern_so2=_acmilan1718t|\nleftarm2=185E0B |body2=185E0B |rightarm2=000000|shorts2=000000|socks2=000000\n|\n|}}\nThe Mayo County Board of the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA) ({{lang-ga|Cumann Luthchleas Gael Coiste Maigh Eo}}) or '''Mayo GAA''' is one of the 32 [[GAA county|county boards]] of the GAA in Ireland, and is responsible for [[Gaelic games]] in [[County Mayo]] and the Mayo inter-county teams.\n\nMayo's senior [[Gaelic football]] team play in the [[Connacht Senior Football Championship]]. Mayo have won four [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]] wins&mdash;[[1936 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1936]], [[1950 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1950]], [[1951 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1951]] and have won the greatest  number of National Football League titles consecutively (6 from 1934 to 1939). Mayo are also currently the longest serving team the [[National Football League (Ireland)]] division 1, having played there since 1997. Mayo have in recent times become known for reaching All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Finals only to fall at the ultimate hurdle. Mayo hold the Championship record for consecutive losing All-Ireland Senior Football Final appearances, this currently stands at nine.<ref>{{cite news|first=Conor|last=Heneghan|url=http://www.joe.ie/gaa/the-championship/preview-kerry-v-mayo/|title=Preview: Kerry v Mayo|work=JOE.ie|quote=Often derided as eternal optimists and held up as the laughing stock of the GAA world [...] Nobody can simply write off what happened at the hands of Sunday's opponents in two All-Ireland finals in the last decade [...] we will see a repeat of the massacres of recent years.}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1989 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1989]], they reached their first All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final since their last previous appearance in 1951 only to lose to [[Cork GAA|Cork]]. In [[1996 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1996]], a freak point by [[Meath GAA|Meath]] at the end of the final forced a replay, which saw Mayo concede another late score that would deny them victory. [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] bridged an 11-year title gap against them in [[1997 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1997]] with a three-point win, before torturing them by eight points in [[2004 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|2004]] and thirteen points in [[2006 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|2006]].<ref name=despair_cannot_last_forever/>\n\nMayo returned to the All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final in [[2012 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|2012]] only for [[Donegal GAA|Donegal]] to bridge a 20-year gap between titles, helped in no small part by a nightmare opening quarter for Mayo as [[Michael Murphy (Gaelic footballer)|Michael]] Murphy launched a rocket of a shot into the goal after three minutes. Then, in the eleventh minute, [[Colm McFadden]] seized the ball from the grasp of Kevin Keane and slid it into the net for a second Donegal goal. Mayo managed thirteen points to Donegal's two goals and eleven, only got on the scoresheet after sixteen minutes when already two goals behind and never led during the match.<ref name=despair_cannot_last_forever>{{cite news|first=Eamonn|last=Sweeney|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/despair-cannot-last-forever-3237022.html|title=Despair cannot last forever|newspaper=Sunday Independent|publisher=Independent News & Media|date=23 September 2012|accessdate=23 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Lyle|last=Jackson|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/northern-ireland/19693260|title=Donegal 2-11 0-13 Mayo|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|date=23 September 2012|accessdate=23 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=John|last=O'Keeffe|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2012/0924/1224324325933.html|title=Donegal's bite was early, deep and fatal|newspaper=The Irish Times|publisher=Irish Times Trust|date=24 September 2012|accessdate=24 September 2012|quote=... But it was, yet again, a nightmare start comparable to 2004 and 2006... You also must commiserate with Mayo. Yet another All-Ireland final defeat... My only concern for them [Mayo], going into next season, would be that they have a lot of similar forwards and none of them are in the mould of Murphy or McFadden.}}</ref> [[2013 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|2013]] saw Mayo in the final again, and once more coming up short, this time being seen off by [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]], who won by a single point. [[2016 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|2016]] likewise, a single point against Dublin, though this time after a replay; the drawn game featuring two own goals by Mayo players. In the 2017 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final after a thrilling final, Mayo yet again lost to Dublin by a single point. Mayo have now lost 9 finals since 1989 and have not won the All-Ireland since 1951. They are classed as one of the best modern era GAA teams that failed to win an All-Ireland Football Final.\n\n==Crest, colours and supporters==\n{{dablink|For the current season see [[2016 Mayo football season]].}}\nThe team's traditional colours are green and red. The Mayo jersey will commonly be mostly green, with a thick horizontal red stripe just below chest level. These colours are inspired by \"The Green Above The Red\", a [[Irish rebel music|rebel song]].<ref>{{cite book | title=The Spirit of the Nation: Ballads and Songs by the Writers of \"The Nation\" |first=Thomas Osborne |last=Davis |authorlink=Thomas Davis (Young Irelander) |pages=264\u20135 |chapter=The Green above the Red |publisher=James Duffy |location=[[Dublin]] |year=1845 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:COA of County Mayo.png|150px|left|County Mayo coat of arms]]\n\nMayo's current crest is based on the county's coat of arms, which is shown on the left. It features four crosses, each representing a [[diocese]] of the [[Catholic Church]] in Mayo. The Patriarchal or 'double' cross represents the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Tuam|Archdiocese of Tuam]], while the three smaller Passion crosses represent [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Achonry|Achonry]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Killala|Killala]] and [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Galway, Kilmacduagh and Kilfenora|Galway/Kilmacduagh/Kilfenora]]. The [[Irish language|Irish]] root word of the county, ''Maigh Eo'', means \"plain of the yew trees\", and the trees that surround the crest represent this. As well as this, the number of trees is significant, with the nine trees representing the number of [[Barony (Ireland)|baronies]] in the county. The sailing ship represents the county's maritime history, while the red sea below the green hills represents the traditional \"green above the red\" motif of the county.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.resources.teachnet.ie/vmcmahon/history/crests.htm | work=teachnet.ie | title=History Around You: Crests and Coats of Arms | accessdate=28 July 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729043105/http://www.resources.teachnet.ie/vmcmahon/history/crests.htm | archivedate=29 July 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Mayo GAA crest also features the Irish words ''Cr\u00edost Linn'', which translates to \"Christ be with us\".\n\nMayo's current sponsors are Irish sports store chain [[Elverys Sports]]. Their jerseys are provided by Irish manufacturers [[O'Neills|O'Neill's sportswear]].\n\nMayo's unofficial supporters club is Mayo Club '51. Their crest is based on the current GAA crest, with the famous mountain Croagh Patrick in green and the sea beneath it in red, signifying the county's coastline. The name of the club commemorates the year that the Mayo senior footballers last won the Sam Maguire Cup, a year which is synonymous with Mayo football.\n\nTraditionally a football county, Mayo have always had a large support at minor, U21 and senior level.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}Despite a long spell without winning the Sam Maguire Cup, Mayo fans have always had a reputation for being a colourful and loyal group of supporters.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\n===Kit evolution===\n{{col-begin|width=70%; margin:auto}}\n{{col-break}}\n{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = \n | pattern_b  = _redhorizontal\n | pattern_ra = \n | leftarm    = 11AA33\n | body       = 11AA33\n | rightarm   = 11AA33\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = FF0000\n | title      = Original kit\n}}\n{{col-break}}\n{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _whiteborder\n | pattern_b  = _greenhoopedwhitecollar\n | pattern_ra = _whiteborder\n | leftarm    = 078725\n | body       = F00000\n | rightarm   = 078725\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = FF0000\n | title      = Classic kit\n}}\n{{col-break}}\n{{Football kit\n| pattern_la = _Mayo2011\n| pattern_b  = _Mayo2011\n| pattern_ra = _Mayo2011\n| pattern_sh =  _adidasonwhite\n| pattern_so = _juve0506a\n| leftarm = 11AA33\n| body = 11AA33\n| rightarm = 004634\n| shorts = FF0000\n| socks = FF0000\n| title = 2009-11}}\n{{col-break}}\n{{Football kit\n| pattern_la = _mayo12\n| pattern_b  = _mayo12\n| pattern_ra =  \n| pattern_sh =  _adidasonwhite\n| pattern_so = _juve0506a\n| leftarm = 004634\n| body = 004634\n| rightarm = 004634\n| shorts = FF0000\n| socks = FF0000\n| title = 2012-14}}\n{{col-break}}\n{{Football kit\n| pattern_la = _mayo15\n| pattern_b  = _mayo15\n| pattern_ra =  _mayo15\n| pattern_sh =  _red_stripes_adidas\n| pattern_so = _juve0506a\n|leftarm=185E0B |body=185E0B |rightarm=185E0B |shorts=FFFFFF |socks=ff0000\n|title= 2014-16}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Sponsorship===\nThe following is a history of shirt sponsors of the Men's Mayo Senior Football team. The Mayo team are currently sponsored by [[Elverys Sports]], previously known as Staunton's Intersport, and have been since 1999, making it one of the longest running sponsorships in the GAA.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Manufacturer\n! colspan=\"2\" | Sponsor\n|-\n! Years\n! Sponsor\n|-\n|rowspan= \"7\" colspan= \"1\"| [[O'Neills]]\n|-\n|1900 - 1991\n|''No Sponsor''\n|-\n|1992 - 1993\n|[[Univet]]\n|-\n|1994\n|''No Sponsor''\n|-\n|1995 - 1998\n|[[Genfitt]]\n|-\n|1999 - 2002\n|[[Elverys Sports|Staunton's Intersport]]\n|-\n|2003 -\n|[[Elverys Sports]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Gaelic football==\n{{further|Mayo Senior Football Championship}}\n\n===History===\nThough not affiliated through the 1890s, there is strong evidence of GAA activity in Mayo and the rivalry with [[Galway GAA|Galway]] that brought success to both counties from the 1930s on was already in evidence.\nThis history between Mayo and [[Galway GAA|Galway]] has produced two of the finest footballing teams in the game. Between them, the two teams have more than three quarters of the [[Connacht Senior Football Championship|Connacht titles]] that have been contested.\n\nMayo have an unequalled number of consecutive [[National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]] titles. The Mayo team were champions in 1934, 1935, 1936, 1937, 1938, and 1939.\n\n====Early years \u2013 Mayo's first All-Ireland====\nOne of the great turning points in GAA history west of the Shannon was the 1935 [[Connacht Senior Football Championship|Connacht Final]] when 26,000 turned out to see [[National Football League (Ireland)|National League Champions]] Mayo beat the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland champions]] [[Galway GAA|Galway]] in [[Dr. Hyde Park|Roscommon]]. In the 1936 [[Connacht Senior Football Championship|Connacht Final]] Mayo were leading by a goal in the last minute when Brendan Nestor scored an equalising goal for [[Galway GAA|Galway]] \u2013 he raised the flag himself and caused a riot. However, Mayo won the replay and went on to capture their first [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland Title]], beating [[Laois GAA|Laois]] by 4\u201311 (23) to 0\u20135 (5) in the final. The following year, 1937, they were the victim of a Louis Blessing last-minute goal in the All Ireland Semi-Final against [[Cavan GAA|Cavan]] in another match that featured a pitch invasion. It ended Mayo's run of 57 matches without defeat. Mayo dominated the [[National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]] for six years, but pulled out of the 1939\u201340 league in a grievance over the 1939 semi-final, a bad-tempered draw and replay with [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]]. Mayo returned to the competition to win their seventh [[National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]] title in 1941. Unfortunately, due to World War II, the league was suspended for four seasons until 1946, and Mayo were unable to add to these successes.\n\n====1940s and 1950s \u2013 Mayo's greatest ever team====\nFollowing Mayo's 1939 [[Connacht Senior Football Championship|Connacht Final]] victory, it took the team nine years to emerge from [[Connacht Senior Football Championship|Connacht]] again, but they narrowly lost the 1948 [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland Final]] to [[Cavan GAA|Cavan]] and 1949 semi-final to [[Meath GAA|Meath]]. However, they returned to Croke Park in 1950 to win an extraordinary [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland Title]] when [[Louth GAA|Louth]]'s Sean Boyle had his kick-out charged down and Mick Flanagan broke through for a freak winning goal, Mayo winning the game by 2\u20135 (11) to 1\u20136 (9). In 1951 Mayo retained the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland Title]], winning their third title overall, with three late points from [[P\u00e1draig Carney]] (known as the flying doctor because he had returned from the United States to play the game) giving Mayo a 2\u20138 (14) to 0\u20139 (9) win over [[Meath GAA|Meath]]. During this period, Mayo also won the [[National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]] in 1949 and 1954, their eight and ninth titles in this competition. Eight wides and a one-point defeat in the replayed 1955 [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland]] Semi-Final against [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] brought this particular era to an end.\n\nMayo went 12 years without winning another Connacht Championship title, until the Mayo team of the late 1960s won the Connacht Championship in 1967 (destroying Galway's 4-in-a-row All-Ireland hopes in the process) and again in 1969. Mayo also added their tenth National League Title to their collection in 1970, beating Down in the final on a scoreline of 4\u20137 (19) to 0\u201310 (10). Despite this success, the 1970s was arguably the least successful decade in the history of Mayo football, as the team failed to win a Connacht Championship title throughout the decade, coming closest when losing the 1975 final to [[Sligo GAA|Sligo]] following a replay.\n\n====1980\u201389: Mayo's return to regional prominence====\nWhile the team had not won an All-Ireland title since 1951, nor even qualified for the final, the 1980s saw a marked improvement in the team's fortunes. A twelve-year gap was finally bridged in [[1981 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1981]] when [[Sligo GAA|Sligo]] were defeated in the Connacht Final on a scoreline of 0-12 to 0-4 at McHale Park, which was followed by a heavy defeat to a great [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] side, 1-6 to 2-19.\n\nNext year, [[1982 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1982]], brought a heavy Connacht Final defeat at the hands of Galway in [[St Jarlath's Park|Tuam]], and a rematch of the final the [[1983 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|following year]] in Castlebar again saw Galway run out the victors, this time by three points. Mayo had at this stage dropped to Division 2 of the NFL and lost a promotion playoff to Roscommon in early 1984. For the third consecutive [[1984 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|year]], Galway and Mayo met in the Connacht Final, this time in [[Pearse Stadium]], [[Galway]]. The result remained the same, with Galway completing the three-in-a-row, 2-13 to 2-9.\n\nMayo were on the opposite side of the draw to Galway in [[1985 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1985]], and easy victories over [[Leitrim GAA|Leitrim]] (semi-final) and Roscommon in the final, saw them claim the Nestor Cup. The final was notable as it saw the retirement of Roscommon great [[Dermot Earley, Snr]], who was chaired from the pitch by the Mayo players at the end of the match. Dublin lay in wait in the All-Ireland Semi-Final, and Mayo's first championship meeting with the Dubs since 1955 ended in a draw 1-13 to 1-13. The first match saw Mayo player John Finn's jaw broken in mysterious circumstances and tension was high for the replay. However, despite a goal from Padraig Brogan, Dublin made easy work of Mayo in the end, running out winners by eight points, 2-12 to 1-7. Despite this, the year marked as close as Mayo had come to an All Ireland Final since 1955. [[Dermot Flanagan]], [[Willie Joe Padden]] and [[Kevin McStay]] received [[GAA GPA All Stars Awards|All Stars]] in recognition of their performances during the year.\n\nAlthough 1986 saw promotion to Division 1 of the league, the [[1986 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|championship]] campaign ended in disappointment with a Connacht Semi-Final defeat to Roscommon at McHale Park. The [[1987 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|following year]] saw Mayo reach the Connacht Final, going down on this occasion to Galway in a low scoring match, 0-7 to 0-8. [[1988 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1988]] saw the team slide to Division 2, but Connacht wins over Sligo, Leitrim and Roscommon in the final saw them reach another All-Ireland Semi-Final. Reigning All-Ireland champions Meath proved too strong for Mayo, running out 0-16 to 2-5 winners, and then going on to defend their title.\n\nThe 1989 season saw former player [[John O'Mahony (Mayo politician)|John O'Mahony]] take over as manager, and after mixed results in the league, an epic [[1989 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|championship]] ensued. After a draw in the Connacht Semi-Final against Galway in Tuam, Mayo won the replay 2-13 to 1-8 in Castlebar, with goals from [[Liam McHale]] and Anthony 'Larry' Finnerty. The final was played in Castlebar against Roscommon and this too resulted in a draw, 0-12 to 1-9. A further 70 minutes in [[Dr. Hyde Park]] a week later also could not separate the teams, with Mayo eventually running out winners 3-14 to 2-13 after extra time. A scrappy game in the All-Ireland semi-final against [[Tyrone GAA|Tyrone]] ended with Mayo as winners 0-12 to 1-6, and was made famous by the iconic image of a bandaged Willie Joe Padden. Mayo's first [[1989 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|All-Ireland Final]] appearance in 38 years was against [[Cork GAA|Cork]], runners up from the previous two seasons. Cork's experience told in the final, and despite a goal by substitute Finnerty in the middle of the second half, Cork ran out winners on a scoreline of 0\u201317 to 1\u201311. All Stars followed that year for [[Gabriel Irwin]], [[Jimmy Browne]], [[Dermot Flanagan]], Willie Joe Padden and [[Noel Durkin]].\n\n====1990\u201399: Fall and rise====\nDespite winning Connacht titles in 1992 and 1993, the early 1990s was a largely unsuccessful period for Mayo, as Connacht football in general suffered a severe drop in standards between 1990 and 1995.\n\nMayo suffered from a hangover of sorts in [[1990 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1990]], and the championship campaign amounted to just one outing, a 2-11 to 1-12 defeat to Galway in Tuam. The [[1990 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|following season]] proved little better, as after big wins over London and Galway, Mayo faced Roscommon in the Connacht Final. A last minute free from long range by Roscommon's Derek Duggan led to a replay in Dr. Hyde Park, which saw Mayo go down by a single point, 0-13 to 1-9. John O'Mahony stepped down as manager at the end of the season, following a dispute between O'Mahony and the County Board over appointment of team selectors.\n\nFormer Dublin player Brian McDonald took over as manager for the [[1992 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1992]] season, which proved more successful for Mayo. Following a first round replay victory over Galway, Mayo got the better of Sligo in the Connacht semi-final and then Roscommon in the final. This set up a first ever meeting with [[Donegal GAA|Donegal]] in the All-Ireland Semi-Final. In what is widely regarded as one of the worst semi-finals of modern times, Donegal beat Mayo on a scoreline of 0-13 to 0-9, before going on to shock Dublin in the All-Ireland Final. TJ Kilgallon was awarded an All Star at midfield at the end of year awards. A player revolt ultimately saw McDonald pushed out, over allegations concerning his training methods, which were said to include pushing a car around a car park.\n\nFormer Kerry legend [[Jack O'Shea]] took over from McDonald as manager for [[1993 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1993]]. Back-to-back Connacht titles were secured in a poor game against Roscommon, which finished 1-5 to 0-7. Humiliation followed in the All-Ireland Semi-Final against Cork, where Mayo went down by 20 points, 5-15 to 0-10. Kevin O'Neill was a rare bright spot for Mayo, and the young forward ended the year with an All Star. Despite the result, O'Shea remained in place for [[1994 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1994]], a campaign that culminated in defeat in the Connacht final by a Leitrim side now managed by John O'Mahony. This was only Leitrim's second ever Connacht title, and prompted O'Shea to step down.\n\nAnthony Egan took over from O'Shea as manager but [[1995 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1995]] proved a low point for Mayo, with relegation to Division 3 of the NFL followed by an unsuccessful championship which culminated in a defeat in the Connacht final to Galway by 7 points in Tuam.\n\n[[John Maughan]], who had achieved some notable successes as manager of [[Clare GAA|Clare]] including a 1992 [[Munster Senior Football Championship|Munster Championship]] title win, was brought in as manager in an effort to improve the team's standing. Maughan was a former Mayo player and [[Defence Forces (Ireland)|Defence Forces]] officer. He was renowned for the physical fitness regime he imposed on his teams, and the improvements were swift. Mayo won Division 3 of the National League in [[1996 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1996]] before going on to win their third Connacht title of the decade, overcoming Galway in the final. Maughan's side produced their performance of the year in the All-Ireland Semi-Final against [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]], winning by 2\u201313 to 1\u201310, a lobbed goal from 40 metres by [[James Horan (Gaelic footballer)|James Horan]] in the last minute of the game sealing the victory. This was Mayo's first victory against Kerry in the championship since 1951.\n\nIn the All-Ireland Final against [[Meath GAA|Meath]] Ray Dempsey's 45th-minute goal gave Mayo a lead of six points; however a [[Meath GAA|Meath]] comeback, culminating in a last-minute Colm Coyle long-range point, saw the game end in a draw on a scoreline of 1\u20139 to 0\u201312. During a bad-tempered replay \u2013 which included a brawl in which Coyle and [[Liam McHale]], one of Mayo's most influential players, was sent off \u2013 Mayo led by four points at half-time only to succumb to a Tommy Dowd goal, losing the game by one-point on a scoreline of 2\u20139 to 1\u201311. Mayo's efforts saw [[Kenneth Mortimer (Gaelic footballer)|Kenneth Mortimer]], Pat Holmes, [[James Nallen]], Liam McHale and James Horan secure All Stars.\n\nMayo retained the Connacht title in [[1997 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1997]], beating Galway, Leitrim and Sligo in the final. The Galway win was notable as it was Mayo's first victory in Tuam in over 30 years. Mayo went on to reach their second successive All-Ireland Final following a 0\u201313 to 0\u20137 victory over the Leinster Champions, [[Offaly GAA|Offaly]]. However, Mayo again lost out in the final, losing by 0\u201313 to 1\u20137 to [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] in a poor game illuminated by the skill of Kerry forward [[Maurice Fitzgerald (footballer)|Maurice Fitzgerald]]. Mortimer was again honoured with an All Star, with only Pat Fallon joining him from the ranks of the Mayo team.\n\nMayo entered the [[1998 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1998]] Connacht Championship as hot favourites, but once more the spectre of John O'Mahony returned to haunt them as his Galway side ambushed Mayo in the preliminary round in Castlebar. Two goals from [[Ciar\u00e1n McDonald]] couldn't prevent a 2-6 to 1-13 defeat.\n\nIn [[1999 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1999]] Mayo returned to Division 1 of the National Football League and another Connacht title (Mayo's fifth of the decade) followed, after wins over [[New York GAA|New York]], Roscommon and Galway in the final. However, Mayo failed to reach another All-Ireland Final falling to Cork 2-12 to 0-12 in the semi-final. James Horan secured and All Star and manager John Maughan resigned after four tumultuous seasons.\n\n====2000\u201309: Success and failure====\nPat Holmes came on board as manager for the [[2000 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|2000]] season, but his managerial career got off to a poor start with a first round defeat in the Connacht Championship against Sligo. The National Football League provided some relief however, and when the matches resumed in the spring of 2001 Mayo won their eleventh National Football League title, beating archrivals Galway in the final on a scoreline of 0\u201313 to 0\u201312 courtesy of a late point from substitute Marty McNicholas, in what was the only national final played between the two western rivals. This was Mayo's first national title since the NFL victory in 1970. Unfortunately, league success did not transfer to the championship and Mayo lost the Connacht Final to Roscommon following a last minute goal by Gerry Lohan. The introduction of the qualifier system that year meant Mayo got a second chance against Westmeath. This also ended in defeat for Mayo, albeit after extra time, on a scoreline of 1-14 to 0-16.\n\nThe [[2002 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|2002]] Championship again got off to a bad start for Mayo, with defeat in their first game against Galway. Into the qualifiers once more, Mayo fared better this time with wins over Roscommon, Limerick and Tipperary, facing the latter duo for the first time in the championship. In the All-Ireland Quarter Final (the quarter final stage having been added to the championship in 2001), Cork again provided the opposition, Mayo again losing out 0-16 to 1-10.\n\nMayo's failure to win a Connacht title under Holmes and his departure at the end of the 2002 season paved the way for John Maughan's return for a second stint as manager of the team. His first [[2003 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|season]] in charge was not particularly successful however, with Mayo eventually falling to Fermanagh in the last 12 of the championship following a Connacht Final defeat to Galway.\n\nIn [[2004 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|2004]], Mayo regained the Connacht title with ease following facile wins over [[New York GAA|New York]], [[Galway GAA|Galway]] and [[Roscommon GAA|Roscommon]], with none of these teams able to finish their matches within five points of Mayo. Mayo followed this success with a surprise victory over reigning All-Ireland Champions Tyrone in the All-Ireland Quarter Final on a scoreline of 0\u201316 to 1\u201309. However, Mayo's form rapidly deteriorated following this win, and the team struggled to see off surprise semi-finalists [[Fermanagh GAA|Fermanagh]] following a replay before losing the All-Ireland Final to Kerry by eight points on a scoreline of 1\u201320 to 2\u20139. James Nallen and Ciar\u00e1n McDonald made the All Stars team that year.\n\nMayo failed to retain their Connacht title in [[2005 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|2005]] losing to Galway in the final. A three-point victory over [[Cavan GAA|Cavan]] in the qualifiers led to a three-point All-Ireland Quarter-Final defeat to Kerry, bringing to an end Maughan's second spell as manager.\n\nIn [[2006 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|2006]], [[Mickey Moran]] became Mayo's first manager from outside the county since Jack O'Shea managed the team in the early 1990s. Moran guided the team to another Connacht title, beating Galway by a point in the final. Following an unconvincing replay victory over [[Laois GAA|Laois]] in the All-Ireland Quarter-Final, in the Semi-Final against Dublin Mayo produced arguably their greatest performance since the defeat of Kerry ten years previously. Even before the game started tensions were raised by Mayo warming up into the [[Hill 16]] end. They were soon joined by Dublin, and some jostling occurred between players and management teams. The match itself was of high quality and resulted in Mayo coming from seven points behind with 20 minutes remaining to defeat favourites Dublin on a scoreline of 1\u201316 to 2\u201312. Ciar\u00e1n McDonald's winning point from under the [[Croke Park|Hogan Stand]] was a particular highlight. [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] again awaited Mayo in the All Ireland Final and for the third time in 10 years they defeated Mayo, this time on a scoreline of 4\u201315 to 3\u20135. [[Alan Dillon]] won his first All Star award, as did [[Conor Mortimer]], joining his brother Kenneth as an award winner. Despite the relative success of the 2006 season, rumours persisted of divisions between Moran and the Mayo County Board and Moran was not retained as manager for the 2007 season.\n\nIn [[2007 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|2007]], [[John O'Mahony (Mayo politician)|John O'Mahony]] returned as Mayo manager following a 16-year absence during which he had won a Connacht title with [[Leitrim GAA|Leitrim]] (1994) as well as two All-Ireland titles with [[Galway GAA|Galway]] (1998 and 2001) and in his first season led the team to the National League Final, where they were defeated by [[Donegal GAA|Donegal]]. Well beaten by Galway in the Connacht Final, they exited the Championship in the second round of the Qualifiers at the hands of [[Derry GAA|Derry]] in [[Celtic Park, Derry]], a game in which Ciar\u00e1n McDonald made his final appearance for Mayo off the bench.\n\nIn [[2008 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|2008]], after losing the Connacht final by a point once more to Galway, they were narrowly beaten by eventual All Ireland Champions Tyrone in the Qualifiers, 0-13 to 1-9. An injury time point by Peader Gardiner saw Mayo win their first Connacht title since O'Mahony's return, and their 42nd title overall, when they beat Galway in the [[2009 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|2009]] Connacht Final on a scoreline of 2\u201312 to 1\u201314. However, defeat to Meath followed in the All-Ireland Quarter Final, 2-15 to 1-15.\n\n====2010\u20132019: Unsuccessful championship pursuits====\n[[File:MacHale Park, Castlebar, Ireland, November 2016.jpg|300px|thumb|MacHale Park in November 2016]]\n[[2010 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|2010]] was a nadir for Mayo; despite reaching the National League Final, they were beaten by Cork, and defeat in the Connacht Championship first round by Sligo was followed up by an All-Ireland Qualifier Round 1 loss to [[Longford GAA|Longford]]. John O'Mahony immediately stepped down as Mayo manager following the game. The return of 'Johnno' had promised much, but only a single Connacht title was won in that tenure, and the county suffered a number of poor defeats in the Qualifiers.\n\nO'Mahony was replaced by James Horan for the [[2011 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|2011]] campaign. Horan had won a [[Mayo Senior Football Championship]] with [[Ballintubber GAA|Ballintubber]] as manager the previous year. After suffering a scare in London in the first round of the 2011 Connacht Championship, Mayo won that years Championship by beating Roscommon in a rain sodden Dr. Hyde Park. Mayo were underdogs going into the  All-Ireland Quarter Final against reigning All-Ireland Champions Cork, but won by four points. The Championship ended at the Semi-Final stage with a nine-point defeat to Kerry, but the improved performances augured well for the future.\n<ref>[http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2008/0804/1217628486219.html \"Old habits stand to Tyrone in endgame\"]. ''The Irish Times'' (8 August 2008).</ref> [[Andy Moran]] was subsequently selected at full-forward on the All Stars team.\n\nMayo reached the final of the National Football League in [[2012 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|2012]], but lost out to Cork 2-10 to 0-11. Mayo retained the Connacht title with wins over Leitrim and Sligo before defeating [[Down GAA|Down]] in the Quarter Final. Facing reigning champions Dublin in the Semi Final, Mayo survived a Dublin fightback to win 0-19 to 0-16 and reach their first final since 2006. Conceding two goals in the first eleven minutes, Mayo lost the [[2012 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final]] to Donegal by 2-11 to 0-13. Four Mayo players earned All Stars, first timers [[Ger Cafferkey]], [[Keith Higgins]] and [[Lee Keegan]] being joined by Alan Dillon for his second.\n\nIn [[2013 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|2013]], Mayo easily won their third consecutive Connacht Championship, defeating Galway by 17 points, Roscommon by 12 points and London by 16 points, in what was a novel final. They gained revenge against Donegal for the previous year in the Quarter Final, running out winners 4-17 to 1-10. A 6-point win over Tyrone saw Mayo return to the [[2013 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|final]], this time to face Dublin. A close game saw Dublin win by a single point on a scoreline of 2-12 to 1-14.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/gaelic-games/24196065|title=Dublin beat Mayo by a point in All-Ireland football final|work=BBC Sport|date=22 September 2013|accessdate=22 September 2013}}</ref> Higgins and Keegan won their second All Stars, along with a first for [[Colm Boyle]] and [[Aidan O'Shea (Mayo footballer)|Aidan O'Shea]].\n\nEntering his [[2014 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|fourth year]] as manager, Horan guided Mayo to another Connacht title after wins over New York, Roscommon and a final victory over Galway, 3-14 to 0-16. A one-point win over Cork led to Semi-Final match up against Kerry. A fantastic second half performance led to Mayo leading by 5 points going into the last five minutes, however a Kieren Donaghy goal saw the game end in a draw, 1-16 apiece. Controversially, the replay was fixed for Limerick's [[Gaelic Grounds]] due to the unavailability of Croke Park owing to an American Football game taking place there. Another epic match ensued, with the sides once more all square after 70 minutes. Kerry managed to pull away in extra-time, eventually winning 3-16 to 3-13. James Horan stepped down immediately afterwards, having done much to restore the pride to Mayo football, albeit falling just short of winning the All-Ireland. Keith Higgins won his third All Star in a row, with Colm Boyle taking his second and [[Cillian O'Connor]] his first.\n\nMayo began [[2015 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|2015]] with new joint managers Pat Holmes and [[Noel Connelly]]. Defeating Galway in the semi-final, a 6-25 to 2-11 win over Sligo saw Mayo win a record-breaking fifth consecutive Connacht title. Another Quarter Final defeat of Donegal saw Mayo matched once more against Dublin in the semi-final. Seven points down with five minutes to go, a Cillian O'Connor penalty helped Mayo force a draw, 1-15 to 2-12. The replay was played at a high tempo, but after an even first half, Dublin pulled away in the second half to win by 7 points, 3-15 to 1-14. Lee Keegan was selected for his third All Star, and Aidan O'Shea for his second. The winter again saw controversy envelop Mayo, as a player protest against the management led to the resignation of the management team of Holmes and Connelly.\n[[File:Flag of County Mayo.jpg|thumb|right|Mayo county flag flying on the day of the [[2017 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|All-Ireland final in 2017]]|280px]]\n[[Stephen Rochford]] was selected as Mayo manager for [[2016 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|2016]], and a poor league campaign nonetheless saw the side stay in Division 1 of the league for an 18th consecutive year. Going for a sixth successive Connacht title, hot favourites Mayo were shocked in the semi-final by Galway, who ran out winners 0-12 to 1-12. However, Mayo battled through the Qualifiers with unconvincing wins against Fermanagh, [[Kildare GAA|Kildare]] and Westmeath to reach a Quarter Final against Tyrone. In a tight game, Mayo won by a point 0-13 to 0-12. Surprise packets [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] awaited in the Semi-Final, which Mayo won 2-13 to 0-14 to set up an All-Ireland Final meeting with Dublin. The game ended in a draw, Mayo battled back after conceding two unfortunate own goals from Kevin McLoughlin and Colm Boyle. Cillian O'Connor got a 77th minute equalising point to bring it to a replay, the game finishing 0-15 to 2-09\nThe replay ended yet another All-Ireland Final defeat by a single point. Cillian O'Connor had the chance with a free to bring the game to extra time in the 76th minute he missed it. It finished 1-15 to 1-14.\n\nIt took them eight games to get to the [[2017 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|All-Ireland final in 2017]]. A bad start turned into a roller coaster, and after their loss to [[Galway GAA|Galway]] would need extra time in two matches to ultimately end up in the final. After a quick concession of a goal to [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]], Mayo took grip of the final and were in control for most of the first half, leading by a point at half time. However Dublin bounced back and a late free deep into extra time would see Dublin edge out winners, on a score line of 1-17 to 1-16, beating Mayo by a point for the second year in a row.\n\nAnother poor league campaign in 2018 put Mayo to the pin of their collar when a last gasp point by Kevin McLoughlin salvaged a draw against a Donegal side who were relegated in the process by not winning the game. Mayo pressed on towards the Connacht championship, which saw them beaten again by Connacht rivals Galway. Mayo had to take the qualifier route yet again, and despite ruthlessly punishing a very poor Limerick side in Round One, Mayo had to earn a hard-fought win over Tipperary to secure their place in the next draw against Kildare.\n\nIn recent years, Mayo's ability to bounce back from heartbreak would become enough to help them navigate through the qualifiers, but it simply wasn't enough against a rejuvenated Kildare side who won the game 0-21 to 0-19 winners. Stephen Rochford had stepped down not long after the defeat, citing that he \"didn't have the backing of the board\". With a vacant position up for grabs, the process had begun in finding the next Mayo manager for 2019.\n\n'''2019: James Horan's return to the managerial position'''\n\n===1951 curse===\nSince the 1990s, a [[sports-related curses|sports curse]] story has circulated that Mayo will not win another All-Ireland until all members of the 1951 team have died.<ref name=\"it3214371\"/> The supposed cause was that the 1951 champions, returning through [[Foxford]] in a coach or lorry, passed a [[funeral cort\u00e8ge]] without respectfully suspending their boisterous celebrations, and were cursed by either the priest, the bereaved spouse, or a [[Irish Travellers|Traveller]].<ref name=\"it3214371\"/> Folklorist Arlene Crampsie, who conducted interviews in Mayo for the 2008\u20132012 GAA [[Oral History]] Project, found that participants had no interest in the story and regarded it as \"recently contrived nonsense\" spread by the media in the wake of multiple recent near-misses.<ref name=\"it3214371\">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/gaelic-games/gaelic-football/the-people-of-mayo-know-the-all-ireland-curse-is-a-contrived-nonsense-1.3214371|title=The people of Mayo know the All-Ireland curse is a contrived nonsense|last=Crampsie|first=Arlene|date=9 Sep 2017|work=[[The Irish Times]]|pages=Sports p.2 |nopp=y|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> In a 2016 [[TG4]] documentary, the two surviving 1951 players, Paddy Prendergast and Padraig Carney, dismissed the story.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/gaelic-games/gaelic-football/mayo-all-ireland-winner-in-1950-and-1951-passes-away-1.2518388|title=Mayo All-Ireland winner in 1950 and 1951 passes away|date=2 Feb 2016|work=[[The Irish Times]]|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> Padraig Carney died on June 9, 2019\u2014leaving only Paddy Prendergast as the sole surviving member of that 1951 team.\n\n===Supporters===\nRespected columnist [[Colm O'Rourke]] has likened the Mayo supporters to [[locust]]s\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Colm|last=O'Rourke|authorlink=Colm O'Rourke|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/gaelic-football/colm-orourke-lets-start-looking-down-under-for-way-to-raise-our-game-38079557.html|title= 'Let's start looking down under for way to raise our game'|work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]|date=5 May 2019|quote=...Mayo supporters will descend like locusts on the South Bronx, and some mightn't even see the game...}}</ref>\n\n===Player Awards===\n\n====All Stars====\nThe annual [[GAA GPA All Stars Awards|GAA All Stars Awards]] recognise the players considered to be the best in their selected positions in the country in any given year. The awards were instituted in 1971 and Mayo's John Carey was among the inaugural selection in that year. Despite winning only two awards in total during their unsuccessful 1970s period, Mayo have been one of the most successful teams nationally in terms of All Star awards gained, with Mayo players winning 42 awards to date. [[Willie Joe Padden]] and Dermot Flanagan became the first Mayo players to win multiple awards, both winning their second awards in 1989. Kenneth Mortimer achieved the same feat in 1997, as did James Horan in 1999 and James Nallen in 2004. Mortimer became the first Mayo player to win back to back awards, winning in both 1996 and 1997, a feat matched by Colm Boyle (2013, 2014 and again, 2016, 2017),  Lee Keegan (2012, 2013, and again, 2015, 2016) and David Clarke (2016, 2017), and exceeded by Keith Higgins, who completed three-in-a-row in 2014. Kenneth and Conor Mortimer became the first Mayo siblings to win awards when Conor won an All Star in 2006.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Player !! Position\n|-\n| 1971 || [[nathan heaney (Gaelic footballer)|Johnny Carey]] || Right-Full Back\n|-\n| 1979 || [[Nathan Heaney (Gaelic footballer)|Joe McGrath]]|| Left-Full Forward\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1985 || [[Dermot Flanagan]] || Left-Full Back\n|-\n| [[Willie Joe Padden]]|| Midfield\n|-\n| [[Kevin McStay]] || Right-Full Forward\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |1989 || [[Gabriel Irwin]]|| Goalkeeper\n|-\n| [[Jimmy Browne]] || Right-Full Back\n|-\n| Dermot Flanagan|| Left-Full Back\n|-\n| Wille Joe Padden  || Midfield\n|-\n| [[Noel Durkin]] || Left-Half Forward\n|-\n| 1992 || [[TJ Kilgallon]]|| Midfield\n|-\n| 1993 ||[[Kevin O'Neill (Mayo Gaelic footballer)|Kevin O'Neill]]|| Right-Half Forward\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |1996 || [[Kenneth Mortimer (Gaelic footballer)|Kenneth Mortimer]] || Right-Full Back\n|-\n| [[Pat Holmes (Gaelic footballer)|Pat Holmes]] || Right-Half Back\n|-\n| [[James Nallen]] || Centre-Half Back\n|-\n| [[Liam McHale]]  || Midfield\n|-\n| [[James Horan (Gaelic footballer)|James Horan]] || Left-Half Forward\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1997  || Kenneth Mortimer || Right-Full Back\n|-\n| [[Pat Fallon (Gaelic footballer)|Pat Fallon]]|| Midfield\n|-\n| 1999|| James Horan || Left-Half Forward\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2004 || James Nallen || Centre-Half Back\n|-\n| [[Ciar\u00e1n McDonald]] || Centre-Half Forward\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2006 || [[Alan Dillon]] ||Left-Half Forward\n|-\n| [[Conor Mortimer]]  || Right-Full Forward\n|-\n|2011\n|Andy Moran\n|Full Forward\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2012 || [[Ger Cafferkey]] || Full Back\n|-\n| [[Keith Higgins]] || Left-Full Back\n|-\n| [[Lee Keegan]] || Right-Half Back\n|-\n|  Alan Dillon  || Centre-Half Forward\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2013 || Keith Higgins || Left-Full Back\n|-\n| Lee Keegan || Right-Half Back\n|-\n| [[Colm Boyle]]|| Left-Half Back\n|-\n| [[Aidan O'Shea (Mayo footballer)|Aidan O'Shea]]  || Midfield\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2014 || Keith Higgins || Left-Full Back\n|-\n|  Colm Boyle || Left-Half Back\n|-\n| [[Cillian O'Connor]] || Right-Corner Forward\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2015 || Lee Keegan || Right-Half Back\n|-\n| Aidan O'Shea  || Full-Forward\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2016  || David Clarke  || Goalkeeper\n|-\n| Brendan Harrison || Right-Full Back\n|-\n| Lee Keegan || Right-Half Back\n|-\n| Colm Boyle || Centre-Half Back\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\" |2017 || David Clarke || Goalkeeper\n|-\n| Chris Barrett || Right-Full Back \n|-\n| Keith Higgins || Left-Full Back \n|-\n| Colm Boyle || Right-Half Back\n|- \n| Aidan O'Shea || Centre-Half Forward \n|-\n| Andy Moran || Left-Corner Forward\n|}\n\n====Footballer of the Year====\nThe '''GAA & GPA [[All Stars Footballer of the Year]]'''\u2014known for sponsorship reasons as the Vodafone Footballer of the Year\u2014is an annual award given at the end of the Championship season to a footballer who is adjudged to have been the best in Gaelic football. \nPlayers from Mayo have won this twice, with [[Lee Keegan]] winning it in 2016 and [[Andy Moran]] winning it in 2017, Mayo did not win the All-Ireland Championship in either of those years.\n\n* 2016 - [[Lee Keegan]]\n* 2017 - [[Andy Moran]]\n\n====Young Footballer of the Year====\nThe '''GAA & GPA [[All Stars Young Footballer of the Year]]''' (often called simply Young Footballer of the Year) is an annual award given at the end of the Championship season to a young footballer under the age of 21 who is adjudged to have been the best in Gaelic football.\nPlayers from Mayo have won this award more times (4) than players from any other county since the award was instituted in 1997. Both Cillian O'Connor and his brother Diarmuid are the only multiple winners ever of the award, they are also the only set of brothers to win the award.\n\n* 2006 - [[Keith Higgins]]\n* 2011 - [[Cillian O'Connor]]\n* 2012 - [[Cillian O'Connor]]\n* 2015 - [[Diarmuid O'Connor]]\n* 2016 - [[Diarmuid O'Connor]]\n\n====Team of the Century and Team of the Millennium====\n'''The Team of the Century''' was nominated in 1984 by ''[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]'' readers and selected by a panel of experts including journalists and former players.<ref>{{cite book| first=Eoghan| last=Corry| title=The GAA Book of Lists| publisher=Hodder Headline Ireland| year=2005| page=238}}</ref> It was chosen as part of the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]]'s centenary year celebrations. Two Mayo players were chosen on the team. These were [[Se\u00e1n Flanagan]] at Left-Corner-Back and [[Tommy Langan]] at Full-Forward.\n\nSimilarly '''The Team of the Millennium''' was a team chosen in 1999 by a panel of GAA past presidents and journalists. The goal was to single out the best ever 15 players who had played the game in their respective positions, since the foundation of the GAA in 1884 up to the [[Millennium]] year, 2000. Both Flanagan and Langan were also selected on this team, occupying the same positions.\n\n===Current football squad===\n*[[Manager (Gaelic games)|Manager]]: [[James Horan (Gaelic footballer)|James Horan]]\n*[[Selector (sport)|Selectors]]: James Burke, Martin Lally, Daniel Forde, Martin Barrett\n{{GAA squad start}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=1|pos=Goalkeeper|name=[[Rob Hennelly]]|club=[[Breaffy GAA|Breaffy]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=2|pos=Right Corner Back|name=[[Chris Barrett (Gaelic footballer)|Chris Barrett]]|club=[[Belmullet GAA|Belmullet]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=3|pos=Full Back|name=[[Brendan Harrison]]|club=[[Aghamore GAA|Aghamore]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=4|pos=Left Corner Back|name=[[Stephen Coen]]|club=[[Hollymount Carramore GAA|Hollymount Carramore]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=5|pos=Right Half Back|name=[[Lee Keegan]]|club=[[Westport GAA|Westport]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=6|pos=Centre Back|name=[[Colm Boyle]]|club=[[Davitts GAA|Davitts]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=7|pos=Left Half Back|name=[[Paddy Durcan]] ([[Captain (sports)|c]])|club=[[Castlebar Mitchels GAA|Castlebar Mitchels]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=8|pos=Midfield|name=[[Aidan O'Shea (Mayo footballer)|Aidan O'Shea]]|club=[[Breaffy GAA|Breaffy]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=9|pos=Midfield|name=[[S\u00e9amus O'Shea]]|club=[[Breaffy GAA|Breaffy]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=10|pos=Right Half Forward|name=Fionn McDonagh|club=[[Westport GAA|Westport]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=11|pos=Centre Half Forward|name=[[Kevin McLoughlin]]|club=[[Knockmore GAA|Knockmore]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=12|pos=Left Half Forward|name=Fergal Boland|club=[[Aghamore GAA|Aghamore]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=13|pos=Right Corner Forward|name=[[Cillian O'Connor]]|club=[[Ballintubber GAA|Ballintubber]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=14|pos=Full Forward|name=Darren Coen|club=[[Hollymount Carramore GAA|Hollymount Carramore]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=15|pos=Left Corner Forward|name=James Carr|club=[[Ardagh GAA|Ardagh]]}}\n{{GAA squad mid}} \n{{GAA squad player|no=16|pos=Substitute|name=[[Miche\u00e1l Schlingermann]]|club=[[Kiltimagh GAA|Kiltimagh]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=17|pos=Substitute|name=Eoin O\u2019Donoghue|club=[[Belmullet GAA|Belmullet]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=18|pos=Substitute|name=[[Keith Higgins]]|club=[[Ballyhaunis GAA|Ballyhaunis]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=19|pos=Substitute|name=David Drake|club=[[Ballaghadereen GAA|Ballaghadereen]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=20|pos=Substitute|name=[[Tom Parsons (footballer)|Tom Parsons]]|club=[[Charlestown Sarsfields GAA|Charlestown Sarsfields]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=21|pos=Substitute|name=[[Donal Vaughan]]|club=[[Castlebar Mitchels GAA|Castlebar Mitchels]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=22|pos=Substitute|name=Matthew Ruane|club=[[Breaffy GAA|Breaffy]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=23|pos=Substitute|name=[[Conor Loftus]]|club=[[Crossmolina Deel Rovers]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=24|pos=Substitute|name=[[Andy Moran]]|club=[[Ballaghadereen GAA|Ballaghaderreen]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=25|pos=Substitute|name=[[Diarmuid O'Connor]]|club=[[Ballintubber GAA|Ballintubber]]}}\n{{GAA squad player|no=26|pos=Substitute|name=[[James Durcan]]|club=[[Castlebar Mitchels GAA|Castlebar Mitchels]]}}\n{{GAA squad end}}\nSquad as per Mayo v [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]], [[2019 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]] Semi Final, 10 August 2019\n\n===Honours===\n* 3 '''[[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]]s'''\n** [[1936 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1936]], [[1950 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1950]], [[1951 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1951]]\n* 5 '''[[All-Ireland Junior Football Championship]]s'''\n** 1933, 1950, 1957, 1995, 1997\n* 5 '''[[All-Ireland Under-21 Football Championship]]s'''\n** 1967, 1974, 1983, 2006, 2016\n* 7 '''[[All-Ireland Minor Football Championship]]s'''\n** 1935, 1953, 1966, 1971, 1978, 1985, [[2013 All-Ireland Minor Football Championship|2013]]\n* 4 '''[[All-Ireland Vocational Schools Championship]]s'''\n** 1971, 1975, 1982, 1999\n* 12 '''[[National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]]s'''\n** 1934, 1935, 1936, 1937, 1938, 1939, 1941, 1949, 1954, 1970, 2001, 2019, 2020\n* 46 '''[[Connacht Senior Football Championship]]s'''\n** 1901, 1903, 1904, 1906, 1907, 1908, 1909, 1910, 1915, 1916, 1918, 1920, 1921, 1923, 1924, 1929, 1930, 1931, 1932, 1935, 1936, 1937, 1939, 1948, 1949, 1950, 1951, 1955, 1967, 1969, 1981, 1985, 1988, 1989, 1992, 1993, 1996, 1997, 1999, 2004, 2006, 2009, 2011, 2012,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/mayo-find-just-enough-in-absence-of-mortimer-3168735.html|title=Mayo find just enough in absence of Mortimer|accessdate=16 July 2012 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |publisher= |date= 16 July 2012}}</ref> 2013,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hoganstand.com/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=197023|title=Connacht SFC final: O'Connor dashes London's dreams |accessdate=21 July 2013 |work=[[Hogan Stand]] |publisher= |date= 21 July 2013}}</ref> 2014,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/gaelic-football/threegoal-mayo-make-it-fourinarow-in-connacht-30427667.html|title=Three goal Mayo make it four-in-a-row|accessdate=14 July 2014 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |publisher= |date= 13 July 2014}}</ref> 2015<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hoganstand.com/Mayo/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=241213|title=Connacht SFC final: Mayo maul Sligo to complete five-in-a-row |accessdate=30 July 2015 |work=[[Hogan Stand]] |publisher= |date= 19 July 2015}}</ref>\n* 40 '''[[Connacht Minor Football Championship]]s'''\n** 1930, 1931, 1933, 1934, 1935, 1936, 1940, 1946, 1947, 1950, 1953, 1954, 1955, 1957, 1958, 1961, 1962, 1963, 1964, 1966, 1971, 1973, 1974, 1977, 1978, 1979, 1980, 1985, 1991, 1996, 1997, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hoganstand.com/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=197020 |title=Connacht MFC final: Mayo hang on |accessdate=21 July 2013 |work=[[Hogan Stand]] |publisher= |date=21 July 2013}}</ref> 2014,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/gaelic-football/rossies-run-champions-close-before-reape-seals-final-victory-30428563.html |title=Rossies run champions close before Reape seals final victory |accessdate=14 July 2014 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |publisher= |date=14 July 2014}}</ref> 2019\n